    "text": "Heat is the most likely explanation. In hot conditions your body sends extra blood to the skin to shed heat, so the heart often beats faster to support the same easy pace; that can show up as the extra 10 bpm you saw. Your resting picture does not point to broader strain today: resting heart rate is 55 bpm, matching your 55.3 baseline, and HRV is 60 ms, in line with usual. That makes this look like heat-related cardiac drift rather than a watch fault or illness signal. Practical version: for hot easy days, run by feel and let pace slow; save pace targets for cooler mornings.",
